    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "I can't reproduce this:\n\n```\n>>> pd.__version__\n'0.13.1-89-gb5b7436'\n>>> t=pd.DataFrame({'A':['x','y','z']})\n>>> t.sort(['A'], ascending=[True])\n   A\n0  x\n1  y\n2  z\n\n[3 rows x 1 columns]\n>>> t.sort(['A'], ascending=[False])\n   A\n2  z\n1  y\n0  x\n\n[3 rows x 1 columns]\n```\n\nHowever, if `by` isn't passed, then the only information used about `ascending` is whether it's truelike or falselike, and so we have\n\n```\n>>> t.sort(ascending=[True])\n   A\n0  x\n1  y\n2  z\n\n[3 rows x 1 columns]\n>>> t.sort(ascending=[False])\n   A\n0  x\n1  y\n2  z\n\n[3 rows x 1 columns]\n```\n\nNot sure whether it makes more sense to raise if `ascending` is a tuple/list and `by` is `None` or if we should also let the case pass when `ascending` has the right number of elements.\n"
  },
